  "prompt": "Why does shaking a soda cause it to explode?",
  "response": "Shaking a soda causes it to explode due to the release of dissolved carbon dioxide gas. Here's a step-by-step explanation of the process:\n\n1. **Carbonation**: Soda is carbonated, meaning it contains dissolved carbon dioxide (CO2) gas under pressure. The CO2 is dissolved in the liquid when it's bottled or canned.\n\n2. **Equilibrium**: In an undisturbed soda, the CO2 is in equilibrium. Some of the gas remains dissolved in the liquid, while some forms bubbles at the top of the container.\n\n3. **Shaking**: When you shake the soda, you disturb this equilibrium. The mechanical action of shaking introduces energy into the system, causing the dissolved CO2 to come out of solution and form more bubbles.\n\n4. **Nucleation Sites**: Shaking also creates more nucleation sites (tiny imperfections or bubbles) on the inside of the container and within the liquid itself. These sites allow more CO2 to come out of solution and form bubbles.\n\n5. **Pressure Build-Up**: As more CO2 forms bubbles, the pressure inside the container increases. The bubbles also get trapped in the liquid, increasing the overall pressure.\n\n6. **Opening the Container**: When you open the container, the sudden drop in pressure causes the trapped CO2 bubbles to rapidly expand and escape. This rapid expansion of gas pushes the liquid out of the container, causing the soda to fizz and potentially explode.\n\nIn summary, shaking a soda disrupts the equilibrium of dissolved CO2, leading to the formation of more bubbles and increased pressure. When the container is opened, the sudden pressure drop causes the soda to explode as the gas rapidly escapes.",
